pullRequest.body:
Several bug fixes and simple refactoring. The main changes:

- `Monoidal.lean`: In `structural?`, the number of arguments in `getAppFnArgs` matching was wrong (I only considered explicit ones there). Infact, `structural?` is no longer needed since the matching is performed in `eval`. Now the `monoidalCoherence` is `StructuralAtom`, not `Structural`.
- `Coherence.lean`: Unfolding `MonoidalCoherence.hom` by `dsimp` at the beginning of the coherence tactic.


---

I would strongly suggest using Qq to avoid the kind of errors you have spotted and make sure they don't reappear
Pushing in a different direction, I generally advise to avoid using `Qq` unless it is for functionality that is really missing elsewhere.
Not using Qq already caused bugs here though
From another perspective, the bug should have been caught by tests. This PR improves the tests as well.

One argument for `Qq` here is that ``` ``LiftHom.lift #[none, none, none, none, none, none, none, none, e, none] ``` is super fragile, and fails only in the test rather than in the elaborator if the argument order changes.

I tried to use `Qq` this part, but I was not completely successful https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/15335/commits/d886e88ba98dc4b05cc46e426f8dd7bfd1b277f0.

Instead, I would like to suggest using `mkAppM` here to avoid the `none` sequence, which I believe reasonable solutions for this situation.

It seems that the current `Qq` doesn't work well with matching universe variables needed here. See [Zulip](https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/144837-PR-reviews/topic/.2315335.20meta.20code.20for.20monoidal.20categories).

Actually, this part is independent of the other fixes, so I would like to separate it into a future PR to make it easier to review.
Feel free to make it a separate PR yes
Will you split the PR?
I have made #16570.
Are you reverting stuff from this PR accordingly?
Yes, I separated the codes related to `Qq` discussion into #16570.
Why is this in the diff?
It was an oversight in reverting, thanks.
